  "theory": "A pipeline hazard is any condition that prevents the next instruction in the instruction stream from executing during its designated clock cycle.\n\n1. STRUCTURAL HAZARD: Occurs when two or more instructions need the same hardware resource simultaneously. Example: A single unified memory serving both IF (instruction fetch) and MEM (data access) stages simultaneously. Solution: Harvard architecture with separate I-Cache and D-Cache.\n\n2. DATA HAZARD: Occurs when an instruction depends on the result of a previous instruction still in the pipeline. RAW (Read After Write) is most common — I2 reads a register before I1 writes the result. Solution: Data forwarding (bypassing) routes the ALU output directly back to the next instruction's ALU input, eliminating the stall. When forwarding is not possible, stalls (NOP bubbles) are inserted.\n\n3. CONTROL HAZARD: Occurs when a branch instruction changes the PC. Instructions fetched after the branch may be from the wrong path and must be discarded (flushed). Solution: Branch prediction predicts the branch outcome, and flush-on-miss discards wrongly fetched instructions.",
  "keyPoints": [
    "3 types: Structural (hardware conflict), Data (register dependency), Control (branch/PC change).",
    "RAW (Read After Write) is the most frequent — I2 reads register before I1 writes it.",
    "Data forwarding eliminates RAW stalls by routing EX-stage output directly to next ALU input.",
    "Structural hazards resolved by Harvard architecture — separate I-Cache and D-Cache.",
    "Control hazards cause a branch penalty of 1-3 cycles depending on when branch is resolved.",
    "Each pipeline stall = 1 NOP bubble inserted = 1 wasted clock cycle = reduced throughput."
  ],
  "useCases": [
    "Analyzing performance penalties in modern RISC pipelines (MIPS, ARM, RISC-V).",
    "Designing forwarding units and hazard detection logic in processor microarchitecture.",
    "Compiler-level instruction reordering and scheduling to minimize RAW stalls."
  ]
}
